output.crosstab_text:
Among those who graduated five years previously from first degree courses in Allied health and who were working during the 2021-22 tax year, the industry with the highest proportion of graduates was the same for both female and male graduates (Human health and social work activities). The median earnings for females in this industry were £31,000 and for males were £33,500. The biggest difference in proportions was in Human health and social work activities, where the proportion of female graduates was 11.4 % points higher than the proportion of male graduates.

The biggest difference in median earnings was in Construction, where the median earnings of male graduates were £19,700 higher than the median earnings of female graduates. The group with the highest earnings was Male graduates who worked in the Construction industry (median earnings of £46,700). 67.4% of female graduates worked in the top 2 industries (either Human health and social work activities or Education); the equivalent figure for male graduates was 52.6%.
